WEBVTT

00:16.360 --> 00:19.020
IX. TRAGEDY IN THE GRAVE-YARD.

00:19.980 --> 00:25.700
At half-past nine that night Tom and Sid were sent to bed as usual. They said their prayers,

00:25.700 --> 00:31.900
and Sid was soon asleep. Tom lay awake and waited in restless impatience. When it seemed

00:31.900 --> 00:37.980
to him that it must be nearly daylight he heard the clock strike ten. This was despair.

00:38.500 --> 00:42.700
He would have tossed and fidgeted as his nerves demanded, but he was afraid he might wake

00:42.700 --> 00:50.460
Sid, so he lay still and stared up into the dark. Everything was dismally still. By and

00:50.800 --> 00:57.560
of the stillness little scarcely perceptible noises began to emphasize themselves. The ticking

00:57.560 --> 01:04.220
of the clock began to bring itself into notice. Old beams began to crack mysteriously. The

01:04.220 --> 01:10.400
stairs creaked faintly. Evidently spirits were abroad. A measured, muffled snore issued

01:10.400 --> 01:16.020
from Aunt Polly's chamber. And now the tiresome chirping of a cricket that no human ingenuity

01:16.020 --> 01:22.840
could locate began. Next the ghastly ticking of a death watch in the wall at the bed's

01:22.840 --> 01:30.160
head made Tom shudder. It meant that somebody's days were numbered. Then the howl of a far-off

01:30.160 --> 01:35.040
dog rose on the night air and was answered by a fainter howl from a remoter distance.

01:35.740 --> 01:45.360
Tom was in an agony. At last he was satisfied the time had ceased and eternity begun. He

01:45.360 --> 01:51.520
clock chimed eleven, but he did not hear it. And then there came, mingling with his half-formed

01:51.520 --> 01:57.520
dreams, a most melancholy catterwalling. The raising of a neighbouring window disturbed

01:57.520 --> 02:02.320
him. A cry of, "'Scat, you devil!' and the crash of an empty bottle against the back

02:02.320 --> 02:07.860
of his aunt's woodshed brought him wide awake, and a single minute later he was dressed and

02:07.860 --> 02:13.380
out of the window and creeping along the roof of the L on all fours. He meowed with caution

02:13.380 --> 02:18.080
once or twice as he went, then jumped to the roof of the woodshed and thence to the ground.

02:18.700 --> 02:23.540
Huckleberry Finn was there, with his dead cat. The boys moved off and disappeared in

02:23.540 --> 02:28.100
the gloom. At the end of half an hour they were wading through the tall grass of the

02:28.100 --> 02:33.800
graveyard. It was a graveyard of the old-fashioned Western kind. It was on a hill, about a mile

02:33.800 --> 02:38.720
and a half from the village. It had a crazy bored fence around it, which leaned inward

02:38.720 --> 02:44.980
in places, and outward the rest of the time, but stood upright nowhere. Grass and weeds

02:44.980 --> 02:50.160
grew rank over the whole cemetery. All the old graves were sunken in, there was not a

02:50.160 --> 02:55.860
tombstone on the place. Round-topped, worm-eaten boards staggered over the graves, leaning

02:55.860 --> 03:01.860
for support, and finding none. Sacred to the memory of, so-and-so had been painted

03:01.860 --> 03:06.460
on them once, but it could no longer have been read on the most of them now, even if

03:06.460 --> 03:11.500
there had been light. A faint wind moaned through the trees, and Tom feared it might

03:11.500 --> 03:16.340
be the spirits of the dead complaining of being disturbed. The boys talked little, and

03:16.340 --> 03:20.760
only under their breath, for the time and the place and the pervading solemnity and

03:20.760 --> 03:26.100
silence oppressed their spirits. They found the sharp new heap they were seeking, and

03:26.100 --> 03:30.920
ensconced themselves within the protection of three great elms that grew in a bunch within

03:30.920 --> 03:36.340
a few feet of the grave. Then they waited in silence for what seemed a long time. The

03:36.340 --> 03:41.320
mooting of a distant owl was all the sound that troubled the dead's stillness. Tom's

03:41.320 --> 03:46.320
reflections grew oppressive. He must force some talk, so he said in a whisper,

03:46.680 --> 03:52.580
"'Huckie, do you believe the dead people like it for us to be here?' Huckleberry whispered,

03:53.040 --> 03:57.280
"'I wished I'd knowed. It's awful solemn-like, ain't it?'

03:57.280 --> 03:59.620
"'I bet it is.'

03:59.620 --> 04:04.320
There was a considerable pause while the boys canvassed this matter inwardly. Then Tom whispered,

04:04.320 --> 04:08.440
"'Say, Huckie, do you reckon Hoss Williams hears us talkin'?'

04:08.440 --> 04:12.260
"'Oh, course he does—least his spirit does.'

04:12.260 --> 04:18.420
Tom after a pause, "'I wish I'd said Mr. Williams, but I never meant any harm. Everybody called

04:18.420 --> 04:19.480
him Hoss.'

04:19.480 --> 04:24.020
"'A body can't be too particular how they talk about these here dead people, Tom.'

04:24.020 --> 04:29.700
This was a damper, and conversation died again. Presently Tom seized his comrade's arm and

04:30.320 --> 04:34.300
"'Shh! What is it, Tom?' And the two clung together with beating hearts.

04:34.380 --> 04:40.300
"'Shh! There it is again. Didn't you hear it? Ay, there, now you hear it. Lord, Tom, they're

04:40.300 --> 04:42.780
comin'—they're comin' sure. What do we do?'

04:43.320 --> 04:46.240
"'I don't know. Think they'll see us?'

04:46.240 --> 04:50.800
"'Oh, Tom, they can see in the dark—same as cats. I wished I hadn't come.'

04:50.800 --> 04:57.140
"'Oh, don't be feared. I don't believe they'll bother us. We ain't doin' any harm. If we

04:57.140 --> 05:00.320
keep perfectly still, maybe they won't notice us at all.'

05:00.320 --> 05:04.880
"'I'll try to, Tom, but, Lord, I'm all a shiver. Listen!'

05:05.320 --> 05:10.340
The boys bent their heads together and scarcely breathed. A muffled sound of voices floated

05:10.340 --> 05:11.660
up from the far end of the graveyard.

05:12.300 --> 05:14.540
"'Look! See! There!' whispered Tom.

05:14.740 --> 05:15.880
"'What is it?'

05:15.880 --> 05:19.280
"'It's devil fire! Oh, Tom, this is awful!'

05:19.760 --> 05:23.900
Some vague figures approached through the gloom, swinging an old-fashioned tin lantern

05:23.900 --> 05:28.200
that freckled the ground with innumerable little spangles of light. Presently Huckleberry

05:28.200 --> 05:29.280
whispered with a shudder.

05:29.760 --> 05:34.840
"'It's the devils, sure enough—three of them. Lordy, Tom, we're goners. Can you pray?'

05:34.840 --> 05:39.760
"'I'll try, but don't you be feared. They ain't going to hurt us. Now I lay me down

05:39.760 --> 05:40.320
to sleep—I—'

05:40.380 --> 05:42.120
"'Shh! What is it, Huck?'

05:42.120 --> 05:47.980
"'They're humans. One of them is, anyway. One of them's old muff Potter's voice.'

05:47.980 --> 05:53.880
"'No, taint so, is it? I bet I know it. Don't you stir nor budge. He ain't got

05:53.880 --> 05:58.280
taint sharp enough to notice us. Drunk the same as usual, likely. Blamed old rip.'

05:59.000 --> 06:03.580
"'All right, I'll keep still. Now they're stuck. Can't find it. Here they come again.

06:03.940 --> 06:09.500
Now they're hot. Cold again. Hot again. Red hot. They're pointed right this time. Say,

06:09.660 --> 06:13.240
Huck, I know another of them voices. It's Injun Joe.'

06:13.240 --> 06:18.640
"'That's so, that murdering half-breed. I'd rather they was devils a-durn sight. What

06:18.640 --> 06:20.040
can they be up to?'

06:20.040 --> 06:24.740
The whisper died wholly out now, for the three men had reached the grave and stood within

06:24.740 --> 06:26.260
a few feet of the boy's hiding-place.

06:27.360 --> 06:32.140
"'Here it is,' said the third voice, and the owner of it held up the lantern and revealed

06:32.140 --> 06:37.760
the face of young Dr. Robinson. Potter and Injun Joe were carrying a hand-barrow with

06:37.760 --> 06:41.960
a rope and a couple of shovels on it. They cast down their load and began to open the

06:41.960 --> 06:46.920
grave. The doctor put the lantern at the head of the grave, and came and sat with his back

06:46.920 --> 06:51.020
against one of the elm-trees. He was so close the boys could have touched him.

06:51.680 --> 06:56.160
"'Hurry, men,' he said in a low voice, "'the moon might come out at any moment.'

06:56.790 --> 07:01.760
They growled a response and went on digging. For some time there was no noise but the grating

07:01.760 --> 07:07.300
sound of the spades discharging their freight of mold and gravel. It was very monotonous.

07:07.840 --> 07:13.000
Finally a spade struck upon the coffin with a dull woody accent, and within another minute

07:13.000 --> 07:17.000
or two the men had hoisted it out of the ground. They pried off the lid with their

07:17.000 --> 07:22.020
shovels, got out the body, and dumped it rudely on the ground. The moon drifted from behind

07:22.020 --> 07:26.920
the clouds and exposed the pallid face. The barrow was got ready, and the corpse placed

07:26.920 --> 07:32.280
on it, covered with a blanket, and bound to its place with a rope. Potter took out a large

07:32.280 --> 07:35.760
spring-knife and cut off the dangling end of the rope, and then said,

07:35.880 --> 07:40.220
"'Now the cussed thing's ready, Sawbones, and you'll just out with another five, or

07:40.220 --> 07:41.660
here she stays.'

07:41.660 --> 07:43.660
"'That's the talk,' said Injun Joe.

07:44.060 --> 07:46.040
"'Look here, what does this mean?' said the doctor.

07:46.140 --> 07:49.020
"'You required your pay in advance, and I've paid you.'

07:49.020 --> 07:53.140
"'Yes, and you've done more than that,' said Injun Joe, approaching the doctor who

07:53.140 --> 07:58.060
was now standing. "'Five years ago you drove me away from your father's kitchen one night,

07:58.280 --> 08:02.820
when I come to ask for something to eat, and you said I weren't there for any good, and

08:02.820 --> 08:07.620
when I swore I'd get even with you, if it took a hundred years, your father had me jailed

08:07.620 --> 08:10.060
for a vagrant. Did you think I'd forget?'

08:10.060 --> 08:15.540
"'The Injun blood ain't in me for nothing. And now I've got you, and you got to settle,

08:15.580 --> 08:16.080
you know.'

08:16.080 --> 08:20.880
He was threatening the doctor, with his fist in his face by this time. The doctor struck

08:20.880 --> 08:25.220
out suddenly and stretched the ruffian on the ground. Potter dropped his knife and exclaimed,

08:25.480 --> 08:30.040
"'Here, now, don't you hit my pard!' and the next moment he was grappled with the doctor,

08:30.400 --> 08:34.380
and the two were struggling with might and main, trampling the grass and tearing the

08:34.380 --> 08:38.520
ground with their heels. Injun Joe sprang to his feet, his eyes flaming with passion,

08:38.520 --> 08:43.180
snatched up Potter's knife, and went creeping, cat-like and snooping, round and round about

08:43.180 --> 08:47.900
the combatants, seeking an opportunity. All at once the doctor flung himself free, seized

08:47.900 --> 08:51.940
the heavy headboard of William's grave, and felled Potter to the earth with it, and in

08:51.940 --> 08:56.180
the same instance the half-breed saw his chance and drove the knife to the hilt in the young

08:56.180 --> 09:02.620
man's breast. He reeled and fell partly upon Potter, flooding him with his blood, and in

09:02.620 --> 09:06.660
the same moment the clouds blotted out the dreadful spectacle, and the two frightened

09:06.660 --> 09:12.180
boys went speeding away in the dark. Presently, when the moon emerged again, Injun Joe was

09:12.180 --> 09:16.880
standing over the two forms, contemplating them. The doctor murmured inarticulately,

09:17.240 --> 09:21.560
gave a long gasp or two, and was still. The half-breed muttered,

09:21.980 --> 09:27.280
"'That score is settled, damn you!' Then he robbed the body, after which he put the

09:27.280 --> 09:32.880
fatal knife in Potter's open right hand, and sat down on the dismantled coffin. Three,

09:32.880 --> 09:38.680
four, five minutes passed, and then Potter began to stir and moan. His hand closed upon

09:38.680 --> 09:44.040
the knife. He raised it, glanced at it, and let it fall with a shudder. Then he sat up

09:44.040 --> 09:49.260
pushing the body from him, and gazed at it, and then around him, confusedly, his eyes

09:49.260 --> 09:50.260
met Joe's.

09:50.500 --> 09:53.040
"'Lord, how is this, Joe?' he said.

09:53.380 --> 09:56.040
"'It's a dirty business,' said Joe, without moving.

09:56.380 --> 09:58.260
"'What did you do it for?'

09:59.240 --> 10:04.100
"'I—I never done it. Look here, that kind of talk won't wash.'

10:04.100 --> 10:05.640
Potter trembled and grew white.

10:05.740 --> 10:10.940
"'I thought I'd got sober. I've no business to drink to-night. But it's in my head yet,

10:11.260 --> 10:16.060
worse than when we started here. I'm all in a muddle, can't recollect anything of it hardly.

10:16.480 --> 10:21.980
Tell me, Joe—honest now, old feller—did I do it? Joe, I never meant to, upon my soul

10:21.980 --> 10:27.180
and honour, I never meant to, Joe. Tell me how it was, Joe. Oh, it's awful! And him so

10:27.180 --> 10:32.780
young and promising. Why, you two were scuffling, and he fetched you one with a headboard, and

10:32.780 --> 10:38.120
you fell flat, and then up you come, all reeling and staggering-like, and snatched the knife

10:38.120 --> 10:42.780
and jammed it into him, just as he fetched you another awful clip, and here you've laid,

10:43.060 --> 10:49.440
as dead as a wedge till now. Oh, I didn't know what I was doing. I wish I may die this

10:49.440 --> 10:53.920
minute if I did. It was all on account of the whisky—and the excitement, I reckon.

10:53.920 --> 10:59.000
I never used a weepin' in my life before, Joe. I've fought, but never with weepins.

10:59.240 --> 11:04.240
They'll all say that. Joe, don't tell. Say you won't tell, Joe. That's a good feller.

11:04.400 --> 11:08.740
I always liked you, Joe, and stood up for you, too. Don't you remember? You won't tell,

11:08.840 --> 11:13.720
will you, Joe?" And the poor creature dropped on his knees before the stolid murderer and

11:13.720 --> 11:15.240
clasped his appealing hands.

11:16.300 --> 11:21.160
No. You've always been fair and square with me, Muff Potter, and I won't go back on you.

11:21.160 --> 11:23.600
There, now, that's as fair as a man can say.

11:24.280 --> 11:28.980
Oh, Joe, you're an angel. I'll bless you for this, the longest day I live—and Potter

11:28.980 --> 11:29.740
began to cry.

11:30.360 --> 11:35.460
Come, now, that's enough of that. This ain't any time for blubbering. You be off yonderway,

11:35.460 --> 11:39.220
and I'll go this. Move now, and don't leave any tracks behind you.

11:39.780 --> 11:44.780
Potter started on a trot that quickly increased to a run. The half-breed stood looking after

11:44.780 --> 11:45.640
him, and he muttered—

11:46.120 --> 11:51.140
If he's as much stunned with the lick and fuddled with the rum as he had the look of

11:51.140 --> 11:55.940
being, he won't think of the knife, till he's gone so far he'll be afraid to come back after

11:55.940 --> 12:00.960
it to such a place by himself, chicken-heart. Two or three minutes later the murdered man,

12:01.220 --> 12:06.300
the blanketed corpse, the lidless coffin, and the open grave rendered no inspection

12:06.300 --> 12:10.100
but the moon's. The stillness was complete again, too.

12:14.100 --> 12:15.140
CHAPTER X.

12:15.560 --> 12:18.360
DIRE PROPHECY OF THE HOWLING DOG

12:18.960 --> 12:24.200
The two boys flew on and on toward the village, speechless with horror. They glanced backwards

12:24.200 --> 12:28.600
over their shoulders from time to time, apprehensively, as if they feared they might be followed.

12:29.080 --> 12:33.840
Every stump that started up in their path seemed a man and an enemy, and made them catch

12:33.840 --> 12:39.160
their breath. And as they sped by some outlying cottages that lay near the village, the barking

12:39.160 --> 12:42.520
of the aroused watch-dogs seemed to give wings to their feet.

12:42.820 --> 12:47.620
"'If we can only get to the old tannery before we break down,' whispered Tom in short catches

12:47.620 --> 12:52.440
between breaths, "'I can't stand it much longer.' Huckleberry's hard pantings were his only

12:52.440 --> 12:56.560
reply, and the boys fixed their eyes on the goal of their hopes and bent to their work

12:56.560 --> 13:01.460
to win it. They gained steadily on it, and at last, breast to breast, they burst through

13:01.460 --> 13:06.440
the open door and fell grateful and exhausted in the sheltering shadows beyond. By and by

13:06.440 --> 13:10.840
their pulses slowed down, and Tom whispered, "'Huckleberry, what do you reckon'll come

13:10.840 --> 13:11.640
of this?'

13:11.640 --> 13:15.880
"'If Dr. Robinson dies, I reckon hangin''ll come of it.'

13:15.880 --> 13:17.400
"'Do you, though?'

13:17.400 --> 13:20.000
"'Why, I know it, Tom.'

13:20.000 --> 13:25.820
Tom thought awhile, and he said, "'Who'll tell? We? What are you talkin' about? Suppose

13:25.820 --> 13:30.380
something happened and Injun Joe didn't hang. Why, he'd kill us some time or other, just

13:30.380 --> 13:36.340
as dead sure as we're layin' here. That's just what I was thinkin' to myself, Huck.'

13:36.340 --> 13:41.320
"'If anybody tells, let Muff Potter do it. If he's fool enough, he's generally drunk

13:41.320 --> 13:42.140
enough.'

13:42.140 --> 13:45.720
Tom said nothing, went on thinking. Presently he whispered,

13:45.720 --> 13:50.220
"'Huck, Muff Potter don't know it. How can he tell?'

13:50.220 --> 13:52.200
"'What's the reason he don't know it?'

13:52.200 --> 13:57.000
"'Because he'd just got that whack when Injun Joe done it. Do you reckon he could see anything?

13:57.520 --> 13:59.860
Do you reckon he knowed anything?'

13:59.860 --> 14:06.120
"'By hokey, that's so, Tom. And besides, look here, maybe that whack done for him.

14:06.120 --> 14:11.160
"'No, taint likely, Tom. He had liquor in him. I could see that. And besides, he always

14:11.160 --> 14:16.500
has. Well, when paps full, he might take and belt him over the head with a church and you

14:16.500 --> 14:21.600
couldn't faze him. He says so his own self. So it's the same with Muff Potter, of course.

14:22.020 --> 14:26.960
But if a man was dead sober, I reckon maybe that whack might fetch him. I don't know.'

14:26.960 --> 14:29.160
After another reflective silence Tom said,

14:29.460 --> 14:31.840
"'Hucky, you sure you can keep Mum?'

14:32.300 --> 14:37.400
"'Tom, we got to keep Mum. You know that. That Injun devil wouldn't make any more of drowning

14:37.400 --> 14:42.820
us than a couple of cats, if we was to squeak about this and they didn't hang him. Now look

14:42.820 --> 14:47.580
here, Tom, let's take and swear to one another. That's what we got to do—swear to keep Mum.'

14:48.080 --> 14:52.040
"'I'm agreed. It's the best thing. Would you just hold hands and swear that we—'

14:52.120 --> 14:56.560
"'Oh, no, that wouldn't do for this. That's good enough for little rubbishy common things,

14:56.560 --> 15:01.420
especially with gals, because they go back on you anyway, and blab if they get in a huff.

15:01.680 --> 15:06.680
But there ought to be writing about a big thing like this—and blood.'

15:06.680 --> 15:12.180
Tom's whole being applauded this idea. It was deep and dark and awful. The hour, the

15:12.180 --> 15:17.120
circumstances, the surroundings were in keeping with it. He picked up a clean pine shingle

15:17.120 --> 15:21.680
that lay in the moonlight, took a little fragment of red keel out of his pocket, got the moon

15:21.680 --> 15:27.440
on his work, and painfully scrawled these lines, emphasizing each slow downstroke by

15:27.440 --> 15:31.440
clamping his tongue between his teeth and letting up the pressure on the upstrokes.

15:31.800 --> 15:33.120
See next page.

15:33.720 --> 15:37.860
Huckleberry was filled with admiration of Tom's facility in writing and the sublimity

15:37.860 --> 15:41.760
of his language. He at once took a pin from his lapel and was going to prick his flesh,

15:41.780 --> 15:42.380
but Tom said,

15:42.580 --> 15:47.640
"'Hold on! Don't do that! A pin's brass. It might have vertigrease on it.'

15:48.080 --> 15:52.980
What's vertigrease? It's pison. That's what it is. You just swallow some of it once—you'll

15:52.980 --> 15:53.760
see."

15:53.760 --> 15:59.160
So Tom unwound a thread from one of his needles, and each boy pricked the ball of his thumb

15:59.160 --> 16:01.040
and squeezed out a drop of blood.

16:02.440 --> 16:08.960
Huck Finn and Tom Sawyer swears they will keep mum about this, and they wish they may

16:08.960 --> 16:13.420
drop down dead in their tracks if they ever tell and rot.

16:14.040 --> 16:18.860
In time, after many squeezes, Tom managed to sign his initials using the ball of his

16:18.860 --> 16:24.620
little finger for a pen. Then he showed Huckleberry how to make an H and an F, and the oath was

16:24.620 --> 16:29.520
complete. They buried the shingle close to the wall, with some dismal ceremonies and

16:29.520 --> 16:34.080
incantations, and the fetters that bound their tongues were considered to be locked, and

16:34.080 --> 16:38.920
the key thrown away. A figure crept stealthily through a break in the other end of the ruined

16:38.920 --> 16:40.960
building now, but they did not notice it.

16:41.700 --> 16:43.060
Tom whispered to Huckleberry,

16:43.660 --> 16:46.440
"'Does this keep us from ever telling—always?'

16:47.100 --> 16:52.480
"'Of course it does. It don't make any difference. What happens? We gotta keep mum. We drop down

16:52.480 --> 16:54.400
dead. Don't you know that?'

16:54.400 --> 16:56.600
"'Yes, I reckon that's so."

16:56.600 --> 17:01.040
They continued to whisper for some little time. Presently a dog set up a long, lugubrious

17:01.040 --> 17:05.480
howl just outside, within ten feet of them. The boys clasped each other suddenly in an

17:05.480 --> 17:06.080
agony of fright.

17:06.320 --> 17:08.600
"'Which of us does he mean?' gasped Huckleberry.

17:08.600 --> 17:10.960
"'I don't know. Peep through the crack, quick.'

17:10.960 --> 17:12.220
"'No, you, Tom.'

17:12.220 --> 17:14.180
"'I can't. I can't do it, Huck.'

17:14.180 --> 17:16.460
"'Please, Tom. There it is again.'

17:16.460 --> 17:22.100
"'Oh, Lordy, I'm thankful,' whispered Tom. I know his voice. It's Bull Harbison."

17:22.100 --> 17:28.820
Note. If Mr. Harbison had owned a slave named Bull, Tom would have spoken of him as Harbison's

17:28.820 --> 17:33.340
Bull. But a son, or a dog, of that name was Bull Harbison.

17:33.340 --> 17:38.460
"'Oh, that's good. I tell you, Tom, I was scared to death, and I'd have bet anything

17:38.460 --> 17:43.120
it was a stray dog.' The dog howled again. The boys' hearts sank once more.

17:43.700 --> 17:46.700
"'Oh, my! That ain't no Bull Harbison!' whispered Huckleberry.

17:46.960 --> 17:48.080
"'Do, Tom!'

17:48.080 --> 17:52.420
Tom, quicking with fear, yielded and put his eye to the crack. His whisper was hardly

17:52.420 --> 17:53.260
audible when he said,

17:53.900 --> 17:56.380
"'Oh, Huck, it's a stray dog.'

17:56.980 --> 17:59.600
"'Quick, Tom, quick. Who does he mean?'

17:59.600 --> 18:02.840
"'Huck, he must mean us both. We're right together.'

18:02.840 --> 18:07.080
"'Oh, Tom, I reckon we're goners. I reckon there ain't no mistake about where I'll go

18:07.080 --> 18:08.500
to. I've been so wicked.'

18:09.200 --> 18:13.340
"'Dag-fetch it! This comes of playing hooky and doing everything a feller's told not to

18:13.340 --> 18:17.960
do. I might have been good like Sid if I'd a tried, but no, I wouldn't, of course. But

18:17.960 --> 18:23.340
if ever I get off of this time, I lay I'll just waller in Sunday schools.' And Tom began

18:23.340 --> 18:24.540
to snuffle a little.

18:25.620 --> 18:26.580
"'You bad?'

18:26.580 --> 18:28.700
And Huckleberry began to snuffle, too.

18:28.820 --> 18:35.500
"'Con sound it, Tom Sawyer. You're just old pie, long side of what I am. Oh, lordy, lordy,

18:35.500 --> 18:38.440
lordy! I wished I'd only had half your chance.'

18:38.440 --> 18:39.980
Tom choked off and whispered,

18:40.140 --> 18:43.180
"'Look, Hucky, look! He's got his back to us.'

18:43.180 --> 18:45.000
Hucky looked with joy in his heart.

18:45.420 --> 18:48.540
"'Well, he has, by jingos. Did he before?'

18:48.540 --> 18:54.080
"'Yes, he did. But I—like a fool, I never thought. Oh, this is bully, you know. Now,

18:54.300 --> 18:55.580
who can he mean?'

18:55.580 --> 18:57.700
The howling stopped, and Tom pricked up his ears.

18:57.840 --> 18:59.820
"'Shh! What's that?' he whispered.

18:59.860 --> 19:05.060
"'Sounds like—like hogs grunting. No, it's somebody snoring, Tom.'

19:05.060 --> 19:10.920
"'That is it. Whereabouts is it, Huck? I believe it's down at Tother End. Sounds so, anyway.

19:11.360 --> 19:16.760
Pap used to sleep there sometimes, long with the hogs. But laws bless you, he just lifts

19:16.760 --> 19:21.640
things when he snores. Besides, I reckon he ain't ever coming back to this town any more.'

19:21.640 --> 19:25.040
The spirit of adventure rose in the boy's soul once more.

19:25.040 --> 19:30.920
"'Hucky, do you dare to go if I lead? I don't like too much. Tom's supposed it's Injun Joe.'

19:30.920 --> 19:35.860
Tom quailed. But presently the temptation rose up strong again, and the boys agreed to try,

19:35.880 --> 19:40.560
with the understanding that they would take to their heels if the snoring stopped. So

19:40.560 --> 19:45.260
they went tip-toeing, stealthily down, the one behind the other. When they had got to

19:45.260 --> 19:50.200
within five steps of the snore, Tom stepped on a stick, and it broke with a sharp snap.

19:50.560 --> 19:56.320
The man moaned, writhed little, and his face came into the moonlight. It was Muff Potter.

19:56.940 --> 20:00.980
The boys' hearts had stood still in their hopes, too, when the man moved, but their

20:00.980 --> 20:06.040
fears passed away now. They tip-toed out, through the broken weather-boarding, and stopped

20:06.040 --> 20:11.420
a little distance to exchange a parting word. That long, lugubrious howl rose on the nightmare

20:11.420 --> 20:15.860
again. They turned and saw the strange dog standing within a few feet of where Potter

20:15.860 --> 20:19.800
was lying, and facing Potter, with his nose pointing heavenward.

20:20.580 --> 20:23.780
"'Oh, Jiminy, it's him!' exclaimed both boys, in a breath.

20:24.580 --> 20:29.240
"'Say, Tom, they say a stray dog come howling round Johnny Miller's house about midnight

20:29.240 --> 20:34.580
as much as two weeks ago, and a whipper-wheel come in and lit on a banister and sung the

20:34.580 --> 20:37.780
very same evening, and there ain't anybody dead there yet.'

20:37.780 --> 20:42.960
"'Well, I know that, and suppose there ain't. Didn't Gracie Miller fall in the kitchen

20:42.960 --> 20:45.360
and burn herself terrible the very next Saturday?'

20:46.060 --> 20:50.360
"'Yes, but she ain't dead. And what's more, she's getting better, too.'

20:50.360 --> 20:54.760
"'All right, well, you wait and see. She's a goner just as dead sure as Muff Potter's

20:54.760 --> 20:59.120
a goner. That's what the niggers say, and they know all about these kind of things,

20:59.440 --> 20:59.760
Huck.'

20:59.760 --> 21:01.520
Then they separated, cogitating.

21:02.040 --> 21:06.980
When Tom crept in at his bedroom window, the night was almost spent. He undressed with

21:06.980 --> 21:12.020
excessive caution, and fell asleep congratulating himself that nobody knew of his escapade.

21:12.020 --> 21:18.260
He was not aware that the gently snoring Sid was awake, and had been so for an hour. When

21:18.260 --> 21:23.060
Tom awoke, Sid was dressed and gone. There was a late look in the light, a late sense

21:23.060 --> 21:28.780
in the atmosphere. He was startled. Why had he not been called? Persecuted till he was

21:28.780 --> 21:34.320
up as usual. The thought filled him with boatings. Within five minutes he was dressed and downstairs,

21:34.580 --> 21:38.700
feeling sore and drowsy. The family were still at table, but they had finished breakfast.

21:38.700 --> 21:44.620
There was no voice of rebuke, but there were averted eyes. There was a silence and an air

21:44.620 --> 21:49.520
of solemnity that struck a chill to the culprit's heart. He sat down and tried to seem gay,

21:49.720 --> 21:55.760
but it was uphill work. It roused no smile, no response, and he lapsed into silence and

21:55.760 --> 21:57.380
let his heart sink down to the depths.

21:58.020 --> 22:02.280
After breakfast his aunt took him aside, and Tom was almost brightened in the hope that

22:02.280 --> 22:07.340
he was going to be flogged, but it was not so. His aunt wept over him and asked him how

22:07.340 --> 22:12.660
he could go and break her old heart so, and finally told him to go on and ruin himself

22:12.660 --> 22:17.700
and bring her grey hairs with sorrow to the grave, for it was no use for her to try any

22:17.700 --> 22:22.960
more. This was worse than a thousand whippings, and Tom's heart was soarer now than his body.

22:23.380 --> 22:29.280
He cried, he pleaded for forgiveness, promised to reform over and over again, and then received

22:29.280 --> 22:34.480
his dismissal, feeling that he had won but an imperfect forgiveness and established but

22:34.480 --> 22:40.800
confidence. He left the presence too miserable to even feel revengeful towards Sid, and so

22:40.800 --> 22:45.780
the latter's prompt retreat through the back gateway was unnecessary. He moped to school

22:45.780 --> 22:50.700
gloomy and sad, and took his flogging, along with Joe Harper, for playing hooky the day

22:50.700 --> 22:56.240
before, with the air of one whose heart was busy with heavier woes and wholly dead to

22:56.240 --> 23:01.220
trifles. Then he betook himself to his seat, rested his elbows on his desk and his jaws

23:01.220 --> 23:05.600
in his hands, and stared at the wall with a stony stare of suffering that has reached

23:05.600 --> 23:10.640
the limit and can no further go. His elbow was pressing against some hard substance.

23:11.000 --> 23:15.780
After a long time he slowly and sadly changed his position and took up this object with

23:15.780 --> 23:22.200
a sigh. It was in a paper. He unrolled it. A long, lingering, colossal sigh followed

23:22.200 --> 23:30.160
and his heart broke. It was his brass and iron knob. This final feather broke the camel's

23:30.160 --> 23:30.740
back.

